  <h1>Types of Workplace Harassment</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits employment discrimination &ldquo;because of sex&rdquo; (42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-2(a)),
    and the EEOC and federal courts have construed that prohibition to cover sexual harassment in two principal forms: quid pro
    quo and hostile work environment. Retaliation for opposing harassment is independently prohibited under &sect; 2000e-3(a).
    This guide walks each theory in the order a practitioner usually evaluates them.
  </p>

  <h2>Quid pro quo harassment</h2>
  <p>
    A supervisor or someone with authority over the employee&rsquo;s working conditions conditions a tangible employment benefit
    on the employee&rsquo;s submission to sexual conduct, or imposes a tangible employment detriment because the employee refused.
    The Supreme Court recognized the theory in <em>Meritor Savings Bank, FSB v. Vinson</em>, 477 U.S. 57 (1986), and clarified the
    employer-liability rules in <em>Burlington Industries, Inc. v. Ellerth</em>, 524 U.S. 742 (1998).
  </p>
  <p>The plaintiff must show:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Membership in a protected class on the basis of sex.</li>
    <li>Unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favors, or other verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature.</li>
    <li>The conduct was tied to a tangible employment action (hiring, firing, failing to promote, reassignment with significantly different responsibilities, or a decision causing a significant change in benefits).</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    When a supervisor takes a tangible action, the employer is <strong>vicariously liable as a matter of law</strong> and the
    <em>Faragher</em>/<em>Ellerth</em> affirmative defense is unavailable. That makes quid pro quo with a documented tangible
    action the most valuable category, holding severity constant.
  </p>

  <h2>Hostile work environment</h2>
  <p>
    Unwelcome sex-based conduct sufficiently severe or pervasive to alter the conditions of the victim&rsquo;s employment and create
    an abusive working environment. The controlling federal standard comes from <em>Harris v. Forklift Systems, Inc.</em>, 510 U.S. 17 (1993):
    the work environment must be objectively hostile (a reasonable person would find it abusive) and subjectively hostile (the
    plaintiff actually perceived it as abusive). The conduct must be unwelcome.
  </p>
  <p>Courts weigh:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Frequency of the discriminatory conduct.</li>
    <li>Severity of the conduct.</li>
    <li>Whether physically threatening or humiliating, or a mere offensive utterance.</li>
    <li>Whether it unreasonably interferes with the employee&rsquo;s work performance.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The standard is disjunctive: <em>severe</em> alone is enough; <em>pervasive</em> alone is enough. A single act of sexual assault
    can satisfy &ldquo;severe&rdquo; without any pattern. A two-year course of unwelcome propositions and sexual jokes can satisfy
    &ldquo;pervasive&rdquo; without any one incident standing out. The EEOC&rsquo;s 2024 Enforcement Guidance on Harassment in the
    Workplace (which superseded earlier 1990s-era guidance) describes the modern application of <em>Harris</em> with current examples.
  </p>

  <h2>The Faragher/Ellerth affirmative defense</h2>
  <p>
    When a supervisor creates a hostile environment but takes <em>no</em> tangible employment action, the employer can raise an
    affirmative defense under <em>Faragher v. City of Boca Raton</em>, 524 U.S. 775 (1998), and <em>Ellerth</em>. The employer
    must prove both prongs by a preponderance:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>It exercised reasonable care to prevent and promptly correct sexually harassing behavior &mdash; typically: a published, distributed anti-harassment policy with a clear complaint procedure; training; prompt investigation; and effective remedial action when complaints arise.</li>
    <li>The plaintiff unreasonably failed to take advantage of any preventive or corrective opportunities, or otherwise to avoid harm.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The defense is unavailable when (a) the supervisor took a tangible action against the plaintiff, (b) the complaint procedure
    routed complaints through or near the harasser, (c) the procedure was not communicated to employees, or (d) the procedure
    was demonstrably ineffective in prior cases. For <strong>coworker</strong> (non-supervisor) harassment, the employer is liable
    on a negligence standard: it knew or should have known of the harassment and failed to take prompt remedial action.
  </p>

  <h2>Retaliation under 42 U.S.C. &sect; 2000e-3</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII makes it unlawful for an employer to discriminate against any employee because she has opposed any practice made
    unlawful by Title VII, or because she has made a charge, testified, assisted, or participated in any investigation or proceeding
    under Title VII. The retaliation provision protects:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Opposition activity:</strong> internal complaints, refusing to participate in unlawful conduct, supporting another employee&rsquo;s complaint.</li>
    <li><strong>Participation activity:</strong> filing an EEOC charge, giving testimony, participating in an investigation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The adverse-action standard is broader than for the underlying discrimination claim. Under
    <em>Burlington Northern &amp; Santa Fe Ry. v. White</em>, 548 U.S. 53 (2006), any action that would dissuade a reasonable
    employee from making or supporting a charge is actionable: schedule changes, transfers, exclusion from meetings, undeserved
    negative reviews, and shunning have all qualified in published cases. The plaintiff also does not need to win the underlying
    harassment claim, only to show a reasonable, good-faith belief that the opposed conduct was unlawful.
  </p>

  <h2>Same-sex harassment after Oncale</h2>
  <p>
    Title VII covers harassment between members of the same sex. The Supreme Court resolved a circuit split in
    <em>Oncale v. Sundowner Offshore Services, Inc.</em>, 523 U.S. 75 (1998), holding that sex-based harassment is actionable
    regardless of the sex of the harasser or the victim, provided the harassment occurred &ldquo;because of sex.&rdquo; The plaintiff
    can show that through evidence that:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>The harasser was motivated by sexual desire toward the plaintiff;</li>
    <li>The harasser was hostile to the presence of one sex in the workplace; or</li>
    <li>Comparative evidence shows the harasser treated members of one sex worse than the other in a mixed-sex workplace.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    <em>Bostock v. Clayton County</em>, 590 U.S. 644 (2020), confirmed that Title VII&rsquo;s prohibition on sex discrimination
    necessarily includes discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, which folds harassment of LGBTQ employees
    into the same legal framework.
  </p>

  <h2>Intersectional harassment</h2>
  <p>
    Harassment can combine sex with another protected characteristic &mdash; race, national origin, age, religion, disability,
    pregnancy &mdash; in a way that is more than the sum of its parts. The EEOC and many federal courts recognize intersectional
    claims: for example, harassment directed at Black women specifically, distinct from harassment directed at all women or all
    Black employees. The Pregnant Workers Fairness Act (2023) and the EEOC&rsquo;s implementing regulations have also expanded the
    framework for harassment claims involving pregnancy, childbirth, and related medical conditions, which often overlap with
    sex-based harassment.
  </p>

  <h2>Third-party harassment</h2>
  <p>
    Under 29 C.F.R. &sect; 1604.11(e) and EEOC guidance, an employer can be liable for harassment by non-employees &mdash; customers,
    vendors, clients, patients &mdash; when the employer knew or should have known of the harassment and failed to take prompt,
    appropriate remedial action within its control. Restaurant servers, healthcare staff, retail workers, and field-sales employees
    frequently have these claims. The employer&rsquo;s available remedies are narrower than for employee perpetrators, but the
    duty to investigate and to act on its own side of the relationship remains.
  </p>

  <h2>Picking a theory</h2>
  <p>
    Most plaintiffs plead multiple theories. The intake exercise is to map the facts to the elements: who did what, were they
    a supervisor or coworker, was there a tangible action, did the plaintiff complain, what happened after the complaint. From
    that map fall out the available theories, the available defenses, and the realistic settlement range. A lawyer does this in
    fifteen minutes on the phone &mdash; bring the timeline and the documents.
  </p>
